---
import CityLayout from '../layouts/CityLayout.astro';
---

<CityLayout
  city="Austin"
  state="Texas"
  stateAbbr="TX"
  status="restricted"
  lastUpdated="May 2026"
>
  <Fragment slot="permitRequired">Yes — Type 1, 2, or 3 license required</Fragment>
  <Fragment slot="licenseFee">$789 new / $338 renewal + $47.30 notification</Fragment>
  <Fragment slot="occupancyTax">17% total (11% City + 6% State)</Fragment>
  <Fragment slot="nightsCap">None, but Type 2 has 1,000-foot spacing rule</Fragment>
  <Fragment slot="officialLink"><a href="https://www.austintexas.gov/development-services/short-term-rentals">Austin Development Services — Short-Term Rentals</a></Fragment>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Austin requires <strong>all</strong> short-term rentals — defined as any residential property rented for fewer than 30 consecutive days — to hold a valid operating license from Austin Development Services Code Compliance. The city uses a three-tier system (Type 1, Type 2, Type 3) that determines where and how you can operate.
  </p>

  <div style="background:#fef3c7;border:1px solid #f59e0b;border-radius:8px;padding:1rem;margin:1.5rem 0;">
    <strong>⚠️ Critical Deadline — July 1, 2026:</strong> Starting this date, Airbnb, Vrbo, and Booking.com will be required to display valid Austin STR license numbers on all listings. Unlicensed properties will be removed within 10 days of a city request. If you're operating without a license, you have weeks — not months — to get compliant.
  </div>

  <h2>License Types</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Who It's For</th><th>Key Rules</th><th>Annual Fee</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Type 1</strong></td>
        <td>Owner-occupied</td>
        <td>Owner must live on-site as primary residence; 1 unit per site</td>
        <td>$634/year</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Type 2</strong></td>
        <td>Non-owner-occupied single-family</td>
        <td>Up to 2 units per site; additional units must be ≥1,000 feet apart</td>
        <td>$634/year</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Type 3</strong></td>
        <td>Multi-family / mixed-use</td>
        <td>Greater of 1 unit or 10% of units (multi-family); 25% cap for mixed-use</td>
        <td>$634/year</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>License Application — Step by Step</h2>
  <h3>What You Need</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Copy of owner's driver's license or government ID</li>
    <li>Proof of tenancy (if the applicant is a tenant)</li>
    <li><a href="https://austin.widen.net/s/vfcxw7q8sp/str_agent-authorization-form">Notarized Agent Authorization Form</a> (if applicant is not the property owner)</li>
    <li>As of October 2025: Certificate of Occupancy and proof of insurance are <strong>no longer required</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Fees (Non-Refundable)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>License Fee</th><th>+ Neighbor Notification</th><th>Total</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>New License</td><td>$789.00</td><td>$47.30</td><td><strong>$836.30</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Renewal</td><td>$338.00</td><td>$47.30</td><td><strong>$385.30</strong></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Licenses are now valid for <strong>2 years</strong> (extended from 1 year as of October 2025).</p>

  <h3>How to Submit</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Go to <a href="https://financeonline.austintexas.gov/afo/account_services/hotel/">Austin Finance Online (AFO)</a></li>
    <li>Upload required documents</li>
    <li>Pay fee via credit card or e-check</li>
    <li>Email a copy of the completed application to <a href="mailto:STRLicensing@austintexas.gov">STRLicensing@austintexas.gov</a></li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Taxes — Hotel Occupancy Tax (HOT)</h2>
  <p>Austin charges a combined <strong>17% Hotel Occupancy Tax</strong> on all short-term rental stays:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>City of Austin:</strong> 11%</li>
    <li><strong>State of Texas:</strong> 6%</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Platforms like Airbnb and Vrbo are required to collect and remit HOT on your behalf. However, you must:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>File a <strong>quarterly report</strong> with the City noting how much HOT each platform collected</li>
    <li>File a <strong>zero report</strong> even if you had no rentals during the quarter</li>
    <li>Manually collect and remit HOT for any direct bookings (non-platform revenue)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>HOT questions: <a href="mailto:hotels@austintexas.gov">hotels@austintexas.gov</a> | 512-974-2590 (press 1)</p>

  <h2>Key Operating Rules</h2>

  <h3>Local Contact Requirement</h3>
  <p>If you don't live in the Austin Metro Area (Travis, Williamson, Hays, Bastrop, or Caldwell County), you must designate a local contact who:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Lives within the metro area</li>
    <li>Can respond to emergencies <strong>within 2 hours, 24/7</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Guest Noise Restrictions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>No sound equipment producing more than <strong>75 decibels</strong> at the property line (10 a.m.–10 p.m.)</li>
    <li>No sound equipment audible beyond the property line (10 p.m.–10 a.m.)</li>
    <li>No noise or musical instruments audible to adjacent residences (10:30 p.m.–7 a.m.)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Neighbor Notification</h3>
  <p>The City mails your local contact information to all properties within <strong>100 feet</strong> of your STR at every license issuance and renewal.</p>

  <h3>Info Packet</h3>
  <p>You must place a printed information packet in a conspicuous common area of your STR, containing: local contact info, noise restrictions, parking rules, trash schedule, burn bans, water restrictions, and ADA requirements.</p>

  <h2>Penalties for Non-Compliance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Operating without a valid license: fines and potential listing removal from platforms starting July 1, 2026</li>
    <li>Advertising an unlicensed STR: prohibited under City Ordinance §4-23-34</li>
    <li>Repeated noise or nuisance violations: license revocation</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Recent Changes (2025–2026)</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Date</th><th>Change</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Feb 2025</td><td>STRs became an accessory use in all residential zoning districts</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Oct 2025</td><td>Regulations moved from Land Development Code (Title 25) to Business Regulations (Title 4); license validity extended to 2 years; Certificate of Occupancy & insurance proof removed; tenants can now operate STRs with landlord permission</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Jul 1, 2026</td><td>Platform enforcement deadline — Airbnb/Vrbo/Booking.com must display license numbers and remove unlicensed listings</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Is Austin STR-Friendly?</h2>
  <p>
    Austin is <strong>moderately restrictive</strong>. The city allows STRs citywide with a license, but the Type 2 1,000-foot spacing rule effectively caps the number of non-owner-occupied STRs in dense neighborhoods. The July 2026 platform enforcement will significantly reduce illegal listings. For owner-occupied Type 1 operators, the rules are manageable. For investors looking to run multiple non-owner-occupied properties, Austin is increasingly difficult.
  </p>

